  "response_text": "The cumulative count of whole milk choices across all agents begins at zero at the initial time step. It increases steadily throughout the 32-step simulation period, following an approximately linear trajectory with a constant accumulation rate averaging between 60 and 70 choices per step. By step 10, the total reaches approximately 700 to 750 choices, and by step 20, it rises to roughly 1,350 to 1,450 choices. The simulation concludes with cumulative totals ranging between approximately 1,980 and 2,280 whole milk choices across different runs.\n\nThis sustained linear growth indicates that agents continue to select whole milk consistently throughout the entire 1974-2005 timeframe, suggesting that high initial habit strength and incumbent advantages maintain consumption levels despite the modeled availability of skimmed and semi-skimmed alternatives and social influence mechanisms. All simulation runs begin with identical initial conditions showing no variance, but deviations emerge progressively after approximately five steps. By the final time step, the spread between the minimum and maximum cumulative totals reaches approximately 300 choices. This divergence reflects the stochastic elements embedded in the model, including the Watts-Strogatz network topology, probabilistic interaction thresholds, and random disposition triggering, which generate heterogeneous social influence paths across different simulation instances while producing similar aggregate consumption persistence."
}

